    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.49-53_0002" />
                
                <fw type="curatorial">50</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    62 <hi rend="caps">NORTH FRANKLIN STREET
                        <lb/>
                    WILKES-BARRE
                        <lb/>
                    PENNSYLVANIA</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>April 7th, 1920</dateline>
                
                    <salute>My dear Mr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>A copy of the letter General Anson Mills wrote you prepared me for your letter of March 29th and its enclosures. I am sorry to seem to fail you but I am afraid any possible data that may remain available; is at my Summer Home at <unclear>Rochport</unclear> Mass. Mr. Schlesinger did live in Cleveland &#8212; or Detroit&#8212; and was a well to do tabacconist
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.49-53_0003"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">51</fw>
                
                    at one time &#8212; I do not know whether he is living or not and wish I did, because he was devoted to General Forsyth and I am at a loss to know why I never heard from him at the time of my husband's death. At the request of another scout I sent him + others newspapers but had not even a line from him. There are some magazines I specially saved, with articles by Mr. Schlesinger, Cyrus Lormsend Brady + others, that followed Gen-Forsyth's article written at the request of Harper + Brothers, but they too I fear are at <unclear>Rochport.</unclear>
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.49-53_0004"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">52</fw>
                    
                    <fw type="authorial">2</fw>
                
                    However I will look around here in my winter home + see if by any chance I brought them with me. I thank you for your salutation. It was a great thing to have a man like General Forsyth trust his future to the untried girl I was when we were married. You may not know that he was only four months younger than my father and a Captain of Cavalry when I was born&#8212; Owing to a recent death in the family, my plans are uncertain but I now expect to go to <unclear>Rochport</unclear> about May 15th or June first. Are these dates too distant for
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.49-53_0005"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">53</fw>
                    
                    any possible help in the work you are doing? I copied all the manuscript used by Harper Brothers + <hi rend="caps">D.</hi> Appleton Sons &#8212; or is it Co? for General Forsyth and know how much work you have set yourself to do. With regret that I am not of more help,</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>I am</salute>
                    <salute>Sincerely</salute> 
                    <signed>Natalie S.B. Forsyth
                
                    Widow of 
                    Gen. G.A. Forsyth</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    62 <hi rend="caps">NORTH FRANKLIN STREET
                        <lb/>
                    WILKES-BARRE
                        <lb/>
                    PENNSYLVANIA</hi> <!--printed upside down-->
                </fw>
                       
            </div1>
            
            
